# File Permissions in Linux

## Project description

Managed and Changed file permissions for User, Group and Other in Linux.

## Check file and directory details

![][image1]

## Describe the permissions string

chmod is the command used for changing permissions on 3 different types of users, User, Group and Other, how these can be seen is with the first 10 characters of each line when using ls \-l command in linux for listing everything in lines and their information, the first 10 characters once using this command shows the following:

d \= Directory  
r \= Read permissions  
w \= Write permissions  
x \= Execution permissions  
\- \= No permissions (in Read, Write, and or Execution)

Beyond here, the 9 characters in front of d are in 3 different blocks:

The first block (second, third and fourth character) represent the permissions of the User  
The second block (fifth, sixth and seventh character) represent the permissions of the Group  
The third and last block (eighth, ninth and tenth characters) represent the permissions of Other users.

## Change file permissions

Using ls \-la to list all files and their information, showing their permissions, and changing them using chmod o-w to remove write permissions from Other for project\_k.txt, as well as using chmod g-r to remove the read permissions from Group for project\_m.txt
